Prerequisites:

1. A provisioned Synapse Workspace with a Spark 3.1 pool to run this notbook on.
1. A keyvault to store the secrets necessary for connecting to the anomaly detector api and blob storage.
1. A provisioined anomaly detector api instance.



This first part is necessary to setup the cluster to leverage the SynapseML libraries which are loaded from Maven coordinates.
To start we'll import a bunch of necessary modules and setup values for some resoruces like storage accounts, container, and keyvault that we'll use throughout the rest of the example.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

import pyspark
from pyspark.sql.functions import col
from pyspark.sql.functions import lit
from pyspark.sql.types import DoubleType
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

from notebookutils import mssparkutils
import synapse.ml
from synapse.ml.cognitive import *

#Specify the name of the storage account that is associated with Synapse
storageAccountName = "cgmsynapsetest"
#Specify the container you created in Storage account, you could also initialize a new name here, and Synapse will help you create that container automatically.
containerName = "default"
#Set a folder name in Storage account to store the intermediate data.
intermediateSaveDir = "intermediate"
#set the name of your key vault
keyVaultName = "cgmsynapsevault"

Now that we have libraries and variables set, load the sample csv file and ensure the columns are of the appropriate data types.

The file we're useing is 4 columns.  The first is the timestamp of the event and the next three are numeric features that will be used to identify which records are anomalous.

filePath = "abfss://" + containerName + "@" + storageAccountName + ".dfs.core.windows.net/mad_example.csv"
#Load the sample data CSV file, assuming this is in the storage account that was provisioned with the cluster no keys are necessary.
df = spark.read.format("csv").option("header", "true").load(filePath)

#Ensure the data loaded form the CSV file is treating the features as numeric data
df = df.withColumn("feature0", col("feature0").cast(DoubleType())) \
    .withColumn("feature1", col("feature1").cast(DoubleType())) \
    .withColumn("feature2", col("feature2").cast(DoubleType()))

# Let's inspect the dataframe:
display(df.limit(10))

To use the anomaly detector we must first give some configuration information about the format of the data, and locations and keys of our dependent resources.

This code assumes you've stored your endpoint key for anomaly detector and the connection string for blob storage in keyVault.  If you want to take a short cut you can always hardcode those values here, but its not a best practice to leave keys inline in code.

#Input your key vault information.  The two secrets here are:
# 1. The key of the anomaly detector api
# 2. The connection string to the storage account where the sample file is stored.  To create intermediate files.
anomalyKey = mssparkutils.credentials.getSecret(keyVaultName, "anomalydetectorkey")
connectionString = mssparkutils.credentials.getSecret(keyVaultName, "blobconnstr")

#Specify information about your data.
startTime = "2021-01-01T00:00:00Z"
endTime = "2021-01-02T09:18:00Z"
timestampColumn = "timestamp"
inputColumns = ["feature0", "feature1", "feature2"]

simpleMultiAnomalyEstimator = (FitMultivariateAnomaly()
    .setSubscriptionKey(anomalyKey)
    .setLocation("eastus2")   #use lowercase letter like: southcentralus
    .setOutputCol("results")
    .setStartTime(startTime)
    .setEndTime(endTime)
    .setContainerName(containerName)
    .setIntermediateSaveDir(intermediateSaveDir)
    .setTimestampCol(timestampColumn)
    .setInputCols(inputColumns)
    .setSlidingWindow(200)
    .setConnectionString(connectionString))

model = simpleMultiAnomalyEstimator.fit(df)
type(model)
Now that we've fit the model, we can apply the model to a dataset with the same structure.   In this case we'll be using a differnt subset of the same file, but that is not required.

#set the time range for inferencing
startInferenceTime = "2021-01-02T09:19:00Z"
endInferenceTime = "2021-01-03T01:59:00Z"

result = (model
      .setStartTime(startInferenceTime)
      .setEndTime(endInferenceTime)
      .setOutputCol("results")
      .setErrorCol("errors")
      .setTimestampCol(timestampColumn)
      .setInputCols(inputColumns)
      .transform(df))

display(result.limit(10))

The prior cell shows us that the first rows in the data frame all have null values for the anomaly detection.  This is because our file is 3000 rows, but we only told it to detect anomalies on timestamps that correspond to the last 1000 or so rows of the file.  In order to better examine the results we need to filter the dataframe to the apporpriate timestamp range.

After filtering the data frame we'll also see that not all rows are anomalies so the contributors column will only have data when an anomaly is detected, where isAnomaly will always have a value, and severity will only have a non zero value when isAnomaly is true.

#Trim out all the rows that are before the range we gave for anomaly detection.
rdf = (result.select("timestamp",*inputColumns, "results.contributors", "results.isAnomaly", "results.severity")
    .orderBy("timestamp", ascending=True)
    .filter(col("timestamp") >= lit(startInferenceTime))
    )

#Output the results
display(rdf)
